s":["Bloodstream infection","Human immunodeficiency virus infection","Human papillomavirus infection","Lower respiratory tract infection","Viral hepatitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to Australian mortality data, \u003Cstrong\u003Elower respiratory tract infections\u003C/strong\u003E remain the leading infectious cause of death, particularly affecting elderly populations and those with underlying health conditions. \u003Cstrong\u003EBloodstream infections\u003C/strong\u003E (sepsis) represent the second most common infectious cause of death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus infection\u003C/strong\u003E mortality has decreased significantly since the introduction of antiretroviral therapy. \u003Cstrong\u003EViral hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E causes relatively fewer deaths, though chronic infections can lead to liver complications. \u003Cstrong\u003EHuman papillomavirus infection\u003C/strong\u003E primarily causes morbidity through cancer development rather than direct mortality.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lower respiratory tract infections remain the leading infectious cause of death in Australia.","Most respiratory infection deaths occur in elderly populations and those with comorbidities."],"references":["AIHW. Infectious and communicable diseases. Australian Government. 2024. Available from: https://www.aihw.gov.au/reports/australias-health/infectious-and-communicable-diseases","Australian Bureau of Statistics. Causes of Death, Australia. Australian Government. 2024. Available from: https://www.aihw.gov.au/reports/australias-health/infectious-and-communicable-diseases."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49790"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14849"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49790","links":{"self":"https://app.